# Roguelike Game Outline - Cataclysm Dark Days Ahead Inspired

## Project Overview
A turn-based survival roguelike game with hunger, sleep, time passing, crafting, building, and tactical combat mechanics.

## Core Systems (Phase 1 - Basic Implementation)

### 1. World/Map System
- Grid-based world (20x20 initial map)
- Basic terrain types: floors, walls, doors, stairs
- Procedural map generation with rooms and corridors
- Player starting position

### 2. Player System
- Position tracking (x, y coordinates)
- Health system (HP)
- Basic movement controls (arrow keys)
- Inventory (limited slots)

### 3. Basic UI
- Game map display
- Player status display (HP, position)
- Simple inventory display
- Game messages/log

## Core Survival Systems (Phase 2)

### 1. Needs System
- Hunger mechanics (decreases over time, requires food)
- Thirst mechanics (decreases over time, requires water)
- Sleep mechanics (decreases over time, requires beds/rest)
- Fatigue system

### 2. Time System
- Turn-based progression
- Day/night cycle
- Time tracking (hours, days)

## Combat & Enemies (Phase 3)
- Simple enemy AI (basic movement toward player)
- Combat system (melee attacks)
- Enemy types (various difficulty levels)
- Damage system

## Advanced Systems (Phase 4+)
- Weapons and armor
- Item crafting system
- Building/construction mechanics
- Advanced inventory management
- More enemy types and behaviors
- Vehicle system
- Skill system
- Crafting recipes
- Weather system
- Permadeath options

## Technical Architecture

### CHTM File Structure
- `chtm/rogue.chtm` - Main game interface
- Map display canvas
- UI panels for status, inventory, messages

### Module Structure
- `modules/rogue/rogue.c` - Main game logic
- State management for player, world, items, enemies
- Turn-based game loop
- Procedural generation algorithms

### Key Variables to Track
- `player_x`, `player_y` - Player position
- `player_hp` - Current health
- `hunger_level` - Hunger value (0-100)
- `thirst_level` - Thirst value (0-100)  
- `sleep_level` - Sleepiness value (0-100)
- `turn_count` - Current turn number
- `game_time` - In-game time
- `current_map` - Map identifier
- `inventory` - Player inventory
- `game_message` - Current game message
- `game_status` - Game state (playing, won, lost, menu)

### Control Scheme
- Arrow keys: Move player
- Space: Use item/interact
- E: Examine/interact with objects
- I: Open inventory
- G: Pickup items on ground
- C: Attempt to craft (when crafting station nearby)
- B: Attempt to build (when building materials available)

## File Structure
- `chtm/rogue.chtm` - Main UI layout
- `modules/rogue/rogue.c` - Game logic
- `modules/rogue/data/maps/` - Procedurally generated maps
- `modules/rogue/data/items.txt` - Item definitions
- `modules/rogue/data/enemies.txt` - Enemy definitions
- `modules/+x/rogue.+x` - Compiled module

## MVP (Minimum Viable Product) Requirements
1. Basic map with player character
2. Arrow key movement
3. Health system
4. Simple win/lose conditions
5. Basic UI display

## Expansion Roadmap
1. Add survival mechanics (hunger, thirst, sleep)
2. Add enemies and combat
3. Implement inventory and items
4. Add crafting mechanics
5. Implement building/construction
6. Add skill progression
7. Advanced AI for enemies
8. Weather and environmental effects
9. Vehicle system
10. Multi-map exploration

## Technical Challenges & Considerations
- Turn-based game loop synchronization with UI
- Efficient map rendering (20x20 minimum, potentially larger maps)
- State persistence between sessions
- Procedural generation consistency
- Memory management for large worlds
- Performance optimization for UI updates

## Initial Implementation Steps
1. Create basic map generation algorithm
2. Implement player movement and positioning
3. Create basic UI layout in CHTM
4. Implement simple health and turn mechanics
5. Test and refine basic gameplay
6. Add initial survival mechanics (hunger)
7. Expand to include more complex systems